		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>Decmb 21<hi rend="sup">st</hi> &#47;55</date></p>
				<p>Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Having seen your reply to <persName>Dr Raphall&#39;s</persName> wherein<lb/> you promise favorably to notice my Heb. Grammar in your valuable Pe&#45;<lb/>riodical I trust you will do so in the next Number&#44; as think an extract from<lb/> it put into the circular I am advised to send about will do much towards procuring<lb/> subscribers to the work.  I intend publishing it at 5<add>&#63;</add> though in <placeName>England</placeName> no less<lb/> than 3000 copies were disposed of at double that sum.  I regret very much<lb/> that I am unable to supply you with a copy to enable you to judge for yourself<lb/> of its superiority to any other&#44; as it is deemed by all who are competent to judge<lb/> of it.  The whole of the last edition published in <placeName>London</placeName> 6 months ago I have<lb/> sold previous to my leaving there&#44; with the exception of 6 copies which<lb/> were soon snatched away at my arrival here and consequently I am now in<lb/> want of one&#44; in my professional pursuit as a teacher I shall be happy to present<lb/> you with one of my next Edition&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Remaining&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Your&#39;s very respectfully</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">S. Newman</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>New York 144 Amos St. Hudson St.</placeName></p>
				<p>The <addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>The <addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Editor of the Occident</p>
